text:
Classic lipoma is a type of lipoma.
Classic lipoma has definition A lipoma that is characterized as a benign well-circumscribed tumor, composed of lobules of mature adipocytes, that arises within subcutaneous tissue, deep soft tissues or on the surface of bones..

Kidney lipoma is a type of kidney benign neoplasm, which refers to a non-cancerous growth in the kidneys. It is also known as Lipoma of kidney. This condition occurs when adipocytes (fat cells) accumulate in the kidney tissue, leading to the formation of a lipoma. Kidney lipomas are typically benign and do not require treatment unless they cause symptoms or compress other organs. In some cases, surgical removal may be necessary if the lipoma becomes large enough to cause discomfort or other health issues.

Pleural lipoma is a type of respiratory system benign neoplasm. This statement implies that the growth in question is non-cancerous and originates from fat cells, specifically adipocytes. The location of the lipoma can be found within the pleura, which are thin membranes that line the lungs and other organs to protect them. It is important to note that while lipomas are not cancerous themselves, they may cause compression or irritation to surrounding tissues if they grow large enough.
Breast lipoma is a type of breast benign neoplasm that is composed of lipocytes.
chest wall lipoma is a type of thoracic benign neoplasm that at least derives from some adipocyte and has location in the chest wall.

Gallbladder lipoma is a type of gallbladder benign neoplasm, which means it's a non-cancerous growth in the gallbladder. It is also known as Lipoma of the gallbladder. Gallbladder lipoma is formed by fat cells and typically located in the gallbladder. It doesn't spread to other parts of the body, but it can cause problems if it grows too large or blocks the flow of bile. Surgery is often recommended to remove it if it causes symptoms or becomes too large.

External ear lipoma is a type of auditory system benign neoplasm, characterized by the presence of fat cells in the external ear. It is also known as Lipoma of the External ear or Lipoma of the External acoustic meatus. It can cause symptoms such as hearing loss or discomfort, and may require surgical intervention for removal.

Axillary lipoma is a type of benign fatty tumor that develops in the axilla, which is the area under the arm and shoulder joint. It is also known as lipoma of the axilla or simply lipoma. These tumors are made up of adipose tissue, which is the same type of tissue that makes up fat cells. Axillary lipomas are generally not cancerous, but they can grow over time and may cause discomfort or pain if they press against surrounding nerves. Treatment options for axillary lipomas include observation, injection with corticosteroids to reduce inflammation, or surgical removal of the tumor.
A lipoma of the spermatic cord is a type of paratesticular lipoma that is located in the spermatic cord and derives from fat cells. It is also known as Spermatic Cord Lipoma.

Paratesticular lipoma is a type of reproductive organ benign neoplasm. Paratesticular lipoma is a type of lipoma, which is a benign tumor made up of fat cells. The term "paratesticular" refers to the area surrounding the testicles or the small sac that holds the sperm. Lipoma can occur in this area and can be considered paratesticular lipoma when it forms as a result of fat accumulation in this particular region.

I understand that you are asking about Chondroid Lipoma, which is a specific type of lipoma. Lipomas typically appear as soft, round lumps under the skin and can occur anywhere on the body. However, they are more common in certain areas such as the legs of women. A chondroid lipoma specifically, is a deep-seated, firm, yellow tumors that characteristically occur on the legs of women. Is there anything else you would like to know about this topic?

Extrahepatic bile duct lipoma is a type of benign (non-cancerous) tumor that originates in the extrahepatic bile ducts, which are the parts of the biliary system that lie outside the liver. It is also known as lipoma of the extrahepatic bile duct. Lipomas are typically made up of fat cells, and they can occur in various organs and tissues throughout the body. In this case, it specifically refers to a tumor or growth that develops in the extrahepatic bile duct.

:cholelithiasis rdfs:subClassOf :gallbladder_disease .
text: cholelithiasis is a type of gallbladder disease.

Pinta disease is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results from infection with Treponema carateum, which is transmitted by contact with the skin and mucous membranes of an infected person. The symptoms include pruritic plaques that slowly enlarge and become pigmented and hyperkeratotic.

Dermatomyositis is a type of inflammatory muscle disease characterized by the simultaneous involvement of skin and muscle tissue. It is an autoimmune disorder that affects the muscles, leading to weakness and muscle wasting. The inflammation in dermatomyositis primarily occurs in the muscle bellies, causing a characteristic "shaggy" appearance of the muscles.
Dermatomyositis often precedes polymyositis, which is characterized by inflammation in the muscle bellies without skin involvement. Dermatomyositis can also present with an overlapping pattern of symptoms with other autoimmune diseases such as lupus and rheumatoid arthritis.
Treatment for dermatomyositis typically involves a combination of medications to reduce inflammation, increase muscle strength, and improve overall function. Physical therapy, speech therapy, and occupational therapy may also be necessary to help patients regain their abilities.

Borderline leprosy, also known as dimorphous or midborderline leprosy, is a type of leprosy that is characterized by small, irregularly shaped red plaques. It is thought to be transmitted through droplet spread transmission.

Aortic atherosclerosis is a type of atherosclerosis that affects the aorta, which is the main artery in the body. Atherosclerosis is the thickening and hardening of the arteries due to the buildup of plaque, which is made up of fat, cholesterol, and other substances. The buildup of plaque can narrow the arteries and reduce blood flow, which can lead to serious health problems such as heart disease, stroke, and peripheral vascular disease.
Atherosclerosis of aorta is a specific type of atherosclerosis that affects the aorta, which is the main artery in the body. Atherosclerosis of aorta occurs when the walls of the aorta become thickened and hardened due to the buildup of plaque. This can also narrow the aorta and reduce blood flow, which can lead to serious health problems such as aneurysm, dissection, or rupture.
It is important to maintain a healthy lifestyle to prevent atherosclerosis. This includes eating a diet low in saturated fat and cholesterol, exercising regularly, maintaining a healthy weight, and not smoking. If you have high blood pressure, diabetes, or other risk factors for atherosclerosis, it is important to work with your healthcare provider to manage these conditions and reduce your risk of developing atherosclerosis.

Histoplasmosis pericarditis is a type of inflammation in the lining surrounding the heart (pericardium). Histoplasmosis refers to an infection caused by the fungus Histoplasma capsulatum. When Histoplasmosis affects the pericardium, it is called histoplasmosis pericarditis. It can cause chest pain and other symptoms similar to those of other types of pericarditis, but it is generally less common. Treatment typically involves antifungal medications and may also include pain relief and other supportive measures.

Brown's S Tendon Sheath Syndrome is a condition that affects the extraocular muscles of the eye, specifically the superior oblique muscle. It occurs when the tendon sheath surrounding the muscle becomes inflamed or irritated, causing it to become overly contracted and leading to restricted movement of the eye. This can result in double vision and other visual disturbances. The condition is typically diagnosed through a combination of physical examination, imaging tests (such as MRI or CT scan), and possibly additional testing such as biopsy or nerve conduction studies. Treatment options for Brown's S Tendon Sheath Syndrome may include medications to reduce inflammation and improve tendon sheath function, physical therapy to strengthen the muscle and improve range of motion, and in some cases, surgery to release the overly contracted tendon sheath.

Exhibitionism is a type of paraphilia disorder that involves recurrent, intense sexual arousal and gratification in response to exposing one's genitals to unsuspecting individuals. It is considered a psychological rather than a physical condition, as it does not involve direct physical contact with another person. Exhibitionism can manifest itself through various behaviors, such as flashing or exposing oneself in public places, sending explicit images or videos to others, or engaging in online activities that involve the sharing of sexually explicit content. It is important for individuals who struggle with exhibitionism to seek professional help and support to address their unique needs and challenges.

Leprosy is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results from an infection located in superficial peripheral nerves, skin, mucous membranes of the upper respiratory tract, anterior chamber of the eyes, or testes and has a material basis in Mycobacterium leprae, which is transmitted by droplet spread from infected nasal secretions to exposed nasal and oral mucosa. The infection causes symptoms such as skin lesions, sensory loss, motor loss, and eye damage.

Thalassemia is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the production of hemoglobin, which results in anemia. It is characterized by decreased synthesis of one or more hemoglobin polypeptide chains and can be classified into different types based on the genetic mutations responsible for the condition.

Ehrlichiosis is a primary bacterial infectious disease that results in infection located in leukocytes. It has a material basis in either Ehrlichia chaffeensis or Anaplasma phagocytophilum, which are transmitted by the lone star tick and black-legged tick, respectively. The infection causes symptoms such as headache, muscle aches, fatigue, and rash.
Pleurisy is a type of pleural disease that is characterized by inflammation of the pleura, the lining of the pleural cavity surrounding the lungs.

Tuberculoid leprosy is a type of leprosy that is characterized by the formation of one or more large, elevated plaques with well-defined borders. These plaques are often accompanied by erythema (redness) and may be surrounded by atrophy (death of tissue). Tuberculoid leprosy is usually transmitted through respiratory droplets and can lead to disfigurement if left untreated. It is also known as smooth leprosy or type T leprosy.

Louping ill is a type of viral infectious disease that results in infection in sheep and rarely humans. It has a material basis in the Louping ill virus, which is transmitted by the sheep tick Ixodes ricinus. The symptoms of louping ill include lethargy, muscle pain, fever, and focal neurological signs.

Yes, that is correct. Strawberry gallbladder, also known as cholesterolosis of the gallbladder, is a condition where there is an excessive accumulation of cholesterol in the walls of the gallbladder. It is not uncommon for this to occur in cats and can lead to inflammation, thickening of the gallbladder wall, and even gallstones if left untreated. However, it is important to note that strawberry gallbladder is a rare condition in cats compared to other more common types of gallbladder disease such as cholecystitis or megaesophagus. If you suspect your cat may have this condition, it is important to consult with a veterinarian for proper diagnosis and treatment.
That is correct. Ototoxicity, on the other hand, refers to damage to the inner ear caused by drugs or chemicals. It can lead to hearing loss and tinnitus.

Mumps is a viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in salivary gland, has\_material\_basis\_in Mumps rubulavirus, which is transmitted by droplet spread of saliva or mucus from the mouth, nose, or throat of an infected person, or transmitted by contaminated fomites. The infection has symptom fever, has symptom headache, has symptom muscle aches, has symptom tiredness, has symptom loss of appetite, has symptom swollen and tender salivary glands under the ears or jaw on one or both sides of the face.

:subendocardial_infarction_acute_myocardial_infarction rdfs:subClassOf :acute_myocardial_infarction .
text: subendocardial infarction acute myocardial infarction is a type of acute myocardial infarction.

That is correct. Left bundle branch hemiblock, also known as Left bundle branch block, is a type of heart conduction disease where the electrical signals in the left side of the heart are delayed or blocked. This can lead to reduced blood flow and oxygen supply to the body, which can cause symptoms such as chest pain, shortness of breath, and dizziness. Treatment may involve medications or other interventions to improve heart function and reduce the risk of complications. It is important to consult a healthcare professional if you suspect that you have this condition.

That is correct. Heart conduction disease, also known as heart rhythm disease, refers to a cardiovascular system disease that affects the electrical conduction system of the heart. It can cause issues with the heart's ability to properly regulate its rhythm and can lead to symptoms such as palpitations, dizziness, and fatigue. Treatment options may include medications, lifestyle changes, and in some cases, surgery or ablation procedures. Is there anything else you would like to know about heart conduction disease?

Prostate cancer is a type of male reproductive organ cancer that occurs when healthy prostate cells grow uncontrollably and form a tumor. The exact synonyms for Prostate Cancer include:

* New growth of prostate (NGP)
* Hereditary prostate cancer
* Malignant tumor of the prostate
* Prostate cancer, familial
* Prostate neoplasm
* Prostatic cancer
* Prostatic neoplasm
* Tumor of the prostate.

Prostate carcinoma is a type of prostate cancer that has its origin in abnormal proliferating cells derived from epithelial cells within the prostate gland. It is also known as carcinoma of the prostate or cancer of the prostate.

Prostate squamous cell carcinoma is a type of prostate cancer that is characterized by the presence of abnormal squamous cells in the prostate gland. It is also known as squamous cell carcinoma of the prostate or SCCP. This type of cancer can be difficult to diagnose and treat compared to other types of prostate cancer, such as adenocarcinoma. It is important for patients to seek medical attention if they experience any symptoms or are at an increased risk for developing this disease.

Yes, that is correct. Prostate malignant phyllodes tumor, also known as malignant Phyllodes neoplasm of the prostate, is a type of cancer that arises from the prostate gland and characterized by the presence of glandular elements and a cellular stroma that exhibits mitotic activity and nuclear atypia. It is important to note that this type of cancer can be aggressive and require prompt treatment.

Familial periodic paralysis is a rare genetic disorder that affects the nerve cells and causes episodes of muscle weakness. These episodes are characterized by flaccid muscles and a loss of deep tendon reflexes. Between these episodes, the affected muscles function normally. The disorder is caused by mutations in certain genes involved in sodium and calcium channel function in nerve cells. It is important to consult with healthcare professionals for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Prostate lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the prostate gland and specifically the lymphocytes present in it. It is also known as Lymphoma of the Prostate or Prostate-Specific Lymphoma. The exact cause of this cancer is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be related to an overactive immune system that attacks healthy cells in the prostate gland.
The symptoms of prostate lymphoma may include pain or discomfort in the lower back, hips, or upper thighs, swelling of the legs and feet, urinary problems, fatigue, fever, weight loss, and night sweats. These symptoms can also be caused by other conditions, so it is essential to consult a medical professional for an accurate diagnosis.
Prostate lymphoma is typically treated with chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or targeted therapies such as monoclonal antibodies. In some cases, surgery may also be necessary to remove the affected prostate gland tissue. The prognosis for prostate lymphoma depends on various factors such as the stage of cancer at diagnosis, the overall health of the patient, and their response to treatment.

Monocular esotropia is a specific type of esotropia, which is characterized by an excessive convergence of the visual axes. This results in a cross-eye appearance and is often seen in infants as they learn to focus on objects. It can also be caused by neurological disorders or conditions that affect eye alignment. In some cases, it can be corrected with glasses or other vision therapies, but in more severe cases, surgery may be necessary.

Raynaud disease is a type of peripheral vascular disease, which is characterized by the abrupt onset of digital paleness or cyanosis in response to cold exposure or stress. It is also known as Raynaud's disease and Raynaud's syndrome. The exact synonyms for this condition are "Raynaud's disease" and "Raynaud's syndrome." It has an exact match with the MESH code D011928.

Parotitis is a type of parotid disease, which is characterized by inflammation of one or both parotid glands. It can cause symptoms such as swelling and pain in the affected area. The exact match for Parotitis is MESH code D010309.

Parotid disease refers to a type of salivary gland disease that specifically affects the parotid gland, which is located in front of the ear and near the jaw. The parotid gland produces a significant amount of saliva, which helps with digestion and keeps the mouth moist. When the parotid gland becomes inflamed or infected, it can cause pain, swelling, and difficulty opening the mouth fully. Parotitis is an example of a specific type of parotid disease that causes inflammation of the parotid gland. It's important to note that while there are other types of salivary gland diseases that can affect multiple glands in the head and neck, they may not always be located near the ear or cause symptoms similar to those experienced with parotitis.

Sialadenitis, also known as sialoadenitis or parotitis, is a type of salivary gland disease characterized by inflammation and swelling of the salivary glands. It can occur due to various factors such as infections, blocked salivary ducts, or autoimmune disorders. Symptoms may include pain, swelling, difficulty swallowing, and excessive saliva production. Treatment typically involves medications to reduce inflammation and antibiotics if the cause is bacterial in nature. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to remove obstructions or damaged gland tissue.

Viral meningitis is a type of infectious disease that affects the brain and spinal cord. It is caused by various viruses, such as the mumps virus or the West Nile virus. Symptoms can include fever, headache, stiff neck, and sensitivity to light. Viral meningitis usually resolves on its own within a few weeks, but it can be serious in some cases, especially if not treated promptly.

Endocarditis is an infection of the inner lining of the heart, typically caused by bacteria. Symptoms may include fever, chest pain, and shortness of breath. It can also cause an enlarged heart or heart failure. Endocarditis occurs when bacteria enter the bloodstream and travel to the heart, where they infect the endocardium. Risk factors for developing endocarditis include having a history of rheumatic fever, heart valve damage, or injection drug use. Treatment typically involves antibiotics and, in some cases, surgery.

Pneumoconiosis is a type of interstitial lung disease that occurs due to the inhalation of dust particles. It can result from exposure to various types of dust, including silica, coal, and asbestos, among others. The condition affects the lungs by causing abnormal pulmonary interstitial morphology and can lead to symptoms such as shortness of breath, coughing, and fatigue. It is crucial to identify and address this condition early on to prevent complications and improve outcomes.

That is correct. Mixed mineral dust pneumoconiosis, also known as mixed dust pneumoconiosis or mixed dust lung disease, occurs when workers inhale a mixture of different types of dust particles, such as silica, coal, and iron oxide. This can lead to the development of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and other respiratory problems over time. It is important for employers to provide proper protective equipment and follow safety guidelines to prevent the onset of this debilitating condition.

Asbestosis is a type of pneumoconiosis caused by inhalation and retention of asbestos fibers. It is characterized by the scarring and stiffening of lung tissue, which can lead to shortness of breath, coughing, and other respiratory symptoms. Asbestosis is typically irreversible once it has developed, but it can be managed with proper medical care and avoidance of exposure to asbestos.

Baritosis is a type of pneumoconiosis that is characterized by the formation of fine, dense lesions in the lung parenchyma caused by long-term exposure to barium dust. These lesions do not affect lung function and disappear without treatment once exposure to the barium dust stops.

That's correct! Berillliosis is a type of respiratory allergy caused by inhalation of beryllium compounds. It can cause symptoms such as cough, fever, and chest pain, and it is considered a serious lung disease. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have been exposed to beryllium or have symptoms of berillliosis.

Byssinosis is a type of pneumoconiosis, which is characterized by hypersensitive reactions to inhaled dust during the initial processing of cotton, flax, or hemp. It can cause symptoms such as chest tightness, cough, and wheezing. The disease has been referred to by several other names, including Flax-dressers' disease, Stripper's asthma, and cotton mill fever.

Anthracosilicosis is a type of pneumoconiosis, which refers to the inhalation of hazardous materials that cause lung damage. Pneumoconiosis, or "black lung," can be caused by various substances including coal dust, silica, and asbestos. Anthracosilicosis specifically refers to the inhalation of carbon and silica dust, which leads to fibrosis (scarring) of the lung tissue. This condition is characterized by shortness of breath and the formation of fibrous nodules in the lungs. It is important for those working with or around these hazardous materials to take precautions to protect themselves from respiratory damage, such as wearing personal protective equipment (PPE) and following proper ventilation guidelines.

Silicosis is a form of pneumoconiosis that results from the inhalation of silica particles, which can lead to inflammation and scarring of the upper lobes of the lungs. This can cause nodular lesions and may affect lung function over time. Silicosis can be caused by exposure to quartz, feldspar, and other minerals containing silica. It is important for individuals who work with these materials to take appropriate precautions, such as using proper respiratory protection equipment, to minimize the risk of developing silicosis.
Caplan's syndrome is a type of pneumoconiosis that occurs in individuals with rheumatoid arthritis. It is also known as Rheumatoid pneumoconiosis.

Anthracosis is a form of pneumoconiosis caused by the inhalation of coal dust, which leads to the deposition of carbon or coal dust in the lung parenchyma and the formation of black nodules. It is also known as Coal Miner's Pneumoconiosis, Coal workers' lung, Coal workers' pneumoconiosis, Melanoedema, and Black Lung.

Siderosis is a specific type of pneumoconiosis that occurs due to the inhalation of iron particles. The excess iron deposits in body tissues, particularly in the lungs and other organs, leading to chronic lung disease. It can also cause other health problems such as anemia, weakness, and fatigue. Siderosis is most commonly seen in workers exposed to iron-rich dust or welding fumes, but it can also occur in individuals with sideropenia (a lack of iron in the diet).

Pulmonary talcosis is indeed a type of pneumoconiosis, which is characterized by fibrosis and granulomatous changes in the lung parenchyma as a result of exposure to talc. The exact synonyms for pulmonary talcosis include pneumoconiosis due to talc and talc pneumoconiosis, as well as talcosis.

Slate pneumoconiosis is a type of occupational lung disease caused by inhaling slate dust. It is characterized by the presence of small, sharp, and hard silicified quartz particles in the lungs, which can cause chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and other respiratory problems. The condition is typically diagnosed through a chest X-ray or other imaging tests that show the presence of nodules or masses in the lungs. Treatment for slate pneumoconiosis may include medical management, such as bronchodilators and corticosteroids, as well as measures to reduce exposure to slate dust, such as the use of personal protective equipment (PPE) by workers who handle slate.
Kaolin pneumoconiosis is a type of pneumoconiosis that occurs due to the inhalation of kaolin dust. It has the same meaning as kaolinosis, which is another name for this condition.

Glaucomatous atrophy of optic disc is a type of optic atrophy, where the optic nerve is damaged due to increased pressure in the eye. This can lead to visual field loss and eventual blindness if not treated. It can be caused by any form of glaucoma and is characterized by an increased optic cup to disc ratio.

:chronic_meningitis rdfs:subClassOf :meningitis .
text: chronic meningitis is a type of meningitis.

Blepharophimosis is a condition characterized by an abnormal narrowness of the palpebral fissure in the horizontal direction due to lateral displacement of the medial canthi of the eyelids. It has a basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth, and is considered an eyelid disease.

The solitary cyst of the breast is a type of benign breast disease. It is characterized by a single, fluid-filled cyst in the breast parenchyma. The cause of these cysts can vary, but they are typically noncancerous and do not spread to other areas of the body. Treatment for solitary cysts generally depends on their size and symptoms. If the cyst is small and causes no discomfort or pain, it may be monitored closely without treatment. However, larger cysts may require surgical intervention, such as aspiration or excision.

Aggressive NK Cell Leukemia is a type of cancer characterized by the proliferation of natural killer cells in the peripheral blood, bone marrow, liver, and spleen. It is associated with Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) and is distinguished from other types of leukemia by its unique cellular composition and clinical features. The term "Large Granular Lymphocyte Leukemia, NK-cell Type" and "Natural Killer Cell Leukemia" are synonymous with Aggressive NK Cell Leukemia.

The term "breast cyst" refers to a type of breast benign neoplasm, which is characterized by a fluid-filled sac in the breast. It's important to note that not all breast lumps are breast cysts; other types of breast lumps can be present as well, such as fibroadenomas or invasive ductal carcinoma. If you have found a lump in your breast, it is advisable to consult with a healthcare professional for proper evaluation and diagnosis.
That is correct, breast fibroadenosis is a type of breast benign neoplasm that is made up of both fibrous and epithelial tissue. It is also known as fibroadenoma or fibroadenosis of the breast.

Fibrosclerosis of the breast is a non-proliferative fibrocystic change that occurs when the tissue in the breast becomes scarred. It is also known as fibrosis of the breast. This condition can cause lumps or bumps to form in the breast and may increase the risk of developing breast cancer. While it is not uncommon for women to experience fibrosclerosis of the breast, it is important to note that not all lumps are cancerous. If you have concerns about a lump in your breast, it's always best to consult with a healthcare professional for a proper evaluation and diagnosis.

Breast fibrocystic disease is a type of benign breast condition characterized by the presence of numerous cysts in the breasts. These cysts are typically round, fluid-filled sacs that can be seen on a mammogram or felt during a physical examination. Breast fibrocystic disease is also sometimes referred to as fibrocystic breast changes or diffuse cystic mastopathy. It is not cancerous and does not require treatment unless it causes significant discomfort or other symptoms.

Chronic leukemia, also known as chronic myeloid leukemia (CML), is a type of cancer that affects the bone marrow and blood cells. It develops slowly over time and can cause anemia, fatigue, and weakness. There are different types of leukemia, but CML is one of the most common forms. The exact cause of CML is not yet fully understood, but it is thought to be related to a genetic mutation that causes the bone marrow cells to produce abnormal white blood cells. Treatment options for CML may include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and stem cell transplantation.

Eosinophilic meningitis is a type of chronic meningitis characterized by the presence of 10 or more eosinophils/microL in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) or a CSF eosinophilia of at least 10 percent. Symptoms of this condition range from mild headache to severe, throbbing headache, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, fever, neck stiffness, paresthesia, and stabbing pain in the trunk and limbs aggravated by touch.

Epididymitis is not the same as Epididymal cancer. Epididymitis is an inflammation or infection of the epididymis, which is a small gland located at the back of the testicle that plays a role in producing sperm. It can cause swelling and pain in the scrotum. On the other hand, Epididymal cancer is a rare type of cancer that occurs in the epididymis, which is a small gland located at the back of the testicle that plays a role in producing sperm. It causes a lump or swelling in the scrotum and can also cause pain. While Epididymitis is typically treated with antibiotics or anti-inflammatory medications, Epididymal cancer is usually treated with surgery or radiation therapy.

Epididymis adenocarcinoma is a type of cancer that affects the epididymis, which is a small gland located at the back of the testicles. Epididymis adenocarcinoma is also known as adenocarcinoma of the epididymis. This type of cancer originates from the epithelial cells that line the glandular structures within the epididymis. It is important to note that this condition has a specific definition, which is an epididymis cancer that derives from epithelial cells of glandular origin. Additionally, there may be related synonyms for this type of cancer, such as adenocarcinoma of the epididymis.

Lymphoid leukemia is a type of cancer that affects the cells in the bone marrow, which are responsible for producing white blood cells. These cells play an essential role in our immune system and help protect our body against infections and illnesses.

In lymphoid leukemia, these cells become abnormal and begin to multiply uncontrollably, leading to an overproduction of white blood cells. As a result, the bone marrow becomes unable to produce enough healthy red blood cells, platelets, and other important cells. This can lead to anemia, fatigue, weakness, easy bruising, and increased risk of infections.

Lymphoid leukemia can be classified into two main types: B-cell and T-cell. B-cell lymphoid leukemia affects a type of white blood cell called B cells, which are responsible for producing antibodies that help fight off infections caused by bacteria and viruses. T-cell lymphoid leukemia affects a different type of white blood cell called T cells, which play an essential role in the immune system's ability to recognize and destroy infected or cancerous cells.

Treatment for lymphoid leukemia usually involves chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and/or bone marrow transplantation. The goal of treatment is to reduce the number of abnormal cells in the body and stimulate the production of healthy blood cells. With early detection and proper treatment, it is possible for people with lymphoid leukemia to achieve a remission or even cure.

yaws is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results in infection located in skin, joint or bone, has\_material\_basis\_in Treponema pallidum subsp pertenue, which is transmitted by direct skin contact with an infected person. The infection has symptom skin lesions.
yaws has exact synonyms: bouba, frambesia, frambesia tropica, frambosie, polypapilloma tropicum and thymosis.

Strabismic amblyopia is a type of amblyopia that occurs due to misalignment of the eyes, also known as strabismus. It is characterized by poor vision in one eye because the brain has begun to ignore it. This condition can be caused by a variety of factors, including genetics and developmental issues. Treatment typically involves correcting the alignment of the eyes through glasses, patching, or surgery, as well as exercises to improve visual acuity. It is important for individuals with strabismic amblyopia to seek medical attention to ensure early detection and proper treatment.

Amblyopia (lazy eye) is a type of eye disease that occurs when the brain favors one eye over the other. This can result in poor vision in the weaker eye, which may wander inward or outward. Amblyopia is often treated with patching or other therapies to encourage the use of both eyes and improve vision.

Refractive amblyopia, also known as ametropic amblyopia, is a type of amblyopia that occurs when refractive errors (such as nearsightedness or farsightedness) are not corrected early in childhood. This can lead to poor development of the visual function in the affected eye(s).

Yes, deprivation amblyopia is a type of amblyopia that occurs due to visual deprivation during the critical period of eye development. It can be caused by conditions such as cataracts, corneal scars, or other structural anomalies that impair vision. The term "disuse" amblyopia is sometimes used synonymously with deprivation amblyopia, although it generally refers to a different type of amblyopia that occurs due to underuse or disuse of the affected eye.

Amyotrophic Neuralgia is a type of Autosomal Dominant Disease, it is also known as Neuralgic Amyotrophy. It is characterized by acute, recurrent episodes of brachial plexus neuropathy with muscle weakness and atrophy preceded by severe pain in the affected arm. The disease has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SEPT9 gene on chromosome 17q25.

Prolymphocytic leukemia, also known as PLL, is a type of chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL). It is characterized by the presence of medium-sized lymphocytes with visible nucleoli in the peripheral blood, bone marrow, and spleen.

Secondary hypertrophic osteoarthropathy, also known as Bamberger-Marie disease and HPOA (hypertrophic pulmonary osteoarthropathy), is a condition that affects the bones and joints. It occurs when there is an excessive growth of bone tissue around the ends of long bones, resulting in thickening and deformity of the bones. This can cause pain, limited mobility, and difficulty breathing. Treatment options may include medications to manage pain and reduce inflammation, as well as physical therapy to improve mobility and strengthen muscles. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to realign or replace affected bones.

Pneumonic plague is a type of lung disease that results from direct inhalation of the bacillus and has symptoms such as fever, chills, cough, and difficulty breathing. It can be transmitted by flea-borne transmission and is characterized by its location in the lungs. Pneumonic plague is also known as primary pneumonic plague or secondary pneumonic plague, depending on whether it is a primary infection or has spread from another source.

Seminal vesicle chronic gonorrhea, also known as Gonococcal seminal vesiculitis, chronic, is a type of gonorrhea that affects the seminal vesicles. It is important to note that while semen can be present in the seminal vesicles, it does not cause the condition. Instead, it's caused by the bacteria Neisseria gonorrhoeae. Symptoms of this condition may include pain or discomfort in the scrotum and testicles, a burning sensation during urination, and fever. If left untreated, it can lead to complications such as epididymitis, orchitis, and infertility. It's important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have seminal vesicle chronic gonorrhea. The condition can be treated with antibiotics, typically by mouth or injection.

Bacterial infectious disease refers to a disease caused by one or more bacteria. It is characterized by infection, inflammation, and the body's immune response against the invading microorganisms. Bacterial diseases can range from mild to life-threatening, depending on the type of bacteria involved and the individual's health status. Some common examples include tuberculosis, salmonella, E. coli, and staphylococcus. Treatment typically involves antibiotics or other medications to kill or inhibit the growth of the bacteria causing the disease. Prevention measures may also be necessary, such as proper handwashing, avoiding close contact with sick individuals, and maintaining a clean living environment.

chronic lymphocytic leukemia (CLL) is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells, particularly the B-cells. It is also known as B-cell chronic lymphocytic leukemia or CLL. The disease causes an excessive production and accumulation of abnormal B-lymphocytes in the bone marrow and blood. This results in a decrease in the number of normal blood cells, particularly red blood cells and platelets.
CLL is primarily found in people over 65 years of age, although it can also occur in younger individuals. Symptoms of CLL may include fatigue, weakness, swollen lymph nodes, weight loss, fever, and an increased risk of infections due to low white blood cell counts.
Treatment options for CLL may vary depending on the stage of the disease and the individual's overall health. Options may include chemotherapy, targeted therapy, radiation therapy, or bone marrow transplant.

gonococcal seminal vesiculitis is not the same as epididymitis, which is inflammation of the epididymis. gonococcal infection can cause epididymitis, but it's a different condition than gonococcal seminal vesiculitis.
gonococcal seminal vesiculitis is a type of gonorrhea that affects the seminal vesicles.
gonococcal seminal vesiculitis is also known as gonorrhea of the seminal vesicle.

acute pericementitis is a specific type of periodontal disease characterized by inflammation and infection of the soft tissue (gingiva) surrounding the teeth. It is often accompanied by swelling, redness, and pain, and can lead to the formation of pus pockets or abscesses if left untreated. Acute pericementitis can be caused by a variety of factors, including bacterial infections, trauma to the gums, and certain medications. It is typically treated with antibiotics, pain relief medication, and sometimes surgery to remove affected tissue. Prevention strategies include regular dental check-ups, proper brushing and flossing techniques, and avoiding habits that put the teeth and gums at risk such as tobacco use and excessive alcohol consumption.

Klippel-Feil syndrome is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the fusion of several cervical vertebrae, leading to severe neck pain and limited mobility. It can also cause deformities in the spine, such as a sunken chest and shoulder blade, as well as a protruding abdomen. Additionally, it can result in other health issues such as scoliosis, kyphosis, and spinal stenosis. Klippel-Feil syndrome is typically diagnosed in childhood and is caused by mutations in the COL2A1 gene, which provides instructions for making a protein called type II collagen.

Stable condition keratoconus is a type of keratoconus that refers to the stage where the progression of the disease has stabilized and not worsening. It is also referred to as stable keratoconus or simply keratoconus.

Purulent acute otitis media is a type of suppurative otitis media. Suppurative otitis media is characterized by the presence of pus in the middle ear, which can result from an infection or inflammation. Purulent acute otitis media specifically refers to this condition with sudden onset and a short course.

Mooren's ulcer is a type of corneal ulcer, which is characterized by painful peripheral corneal ulceration, sterile limbal inflammation, and episcleral and conjunctival edema. It has the exact synonym Mooren ulcer.

Mycotic corneal ulcer is a type of corneal ulcer that occurs due to fungal infection, which can result from minor trauma and subsequent infection by various fungi such as Candida, Aspergillus, Fusarium, and Rhizopus. It causes the cornea to become eroded and ulcerated, leading to pain, redness, and vision loss if left untreated. Early diagnosis and treatment with antifungal medications are crucial for preventing further damage and promoting healing of the affected tissue.

That is correct. A marginal corneal ulcer is a type of corneal ulcer that occurs in the outermost layer of the cornea, specifically at the junction between the cornea and sclera. It is characterized by inflammation and infiltrate formation in the marginal zone, which is parallel but separated from the limbus. Treatment typically involves antibiotics, anti-inflammatory medications, and sometimes corticosteroid therapy to reduce inflammation and promote healing. In severe cases, surgical intervention may be necessary. If you suspect that you have a marginal corneal ulcer, it is important to consult an eye care professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

text: hypopyon is a type of iridocyclitis.

Ring corneal ulcer is a specific type of corneal ulcer that presents with a ring-shaped area of infiltration or ulceration on the cornea. This condition can cause pain, blurred vision, and other symptoms if left untreated. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have a corneal ulcer, as prompt treatment can help prevent further damage to your eye.

That is correct. A perforated corneal ulcer occurs when the cornea becomes thin and ruptures, forming a small hole that may drain or contain pigment. It is a severe form of corneal ulcer that requires immediate medical attention to prevent further damage to the eye.

Tonsillitis is an upper respiratory tract disease that occurs when the tonsils become inflamed. It can be caused by a variety of factors, including bacterial infections (such as Group A streptococcus) and viral infections (such as Epstein-Barr virus or adenovirus). Symptoms may include a sore throat, difficulty swallowing, coughing, headache, fever, and chills. Tonsillitis is typically treated with antibiotics if it is caused by bacteria or antivirals if it is caused by a virus. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to remove the tonsils if they become too large or if there are recurring infections.

Legionnaires disease is a severe form of legionellosis that causes pneumonia. Symptoms may include fever, chills, and cough. It can be transmitted through droplet spread transmission, and it has been shown to have features such as pneumonia. The exact synonyms for Legionnaires disease are Infection by Legionella pneumophilia, Legionella, and Legionella pneumonia.

Legionellosis is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results from infection located in the respiratory tract, has material basis in Legionella pneumophila, and is transmitted by inhalation of droplets containing bacteria. The symptoms include dry cough, fever, headache, and diarrhea.

The common cold is a type of upper respiratory tract disease that affects the mucous membranes of the nose, throat, eyes, and eustachian tubes, causing inflammation and leading to the production of watery or purulent discharge. It is caused by various viruses such as rhinoviruses, human parainfluenza viruses, human respiratory syncytial virus, influenza viruses, adenoviruses, enteroviruses, and metapneumovirus.
Chronic nasopharyngitis is a type of nasopharyngeal disease that involves persistent inflammation of the nasal passages and upper part of the pharynx.

Dentin caries is a type of dental caries that affects the dentin, which is the layer of tooth tissue beneath the enamel. It is also known as compound dental caries and dental caries extending into the dentine.

Correct, patellar tendinitis and patellar tendonitis refer to the same condition. Patellar tendinitis is a common overuse injury that affects the patellar tendon, which connects the kneecap (patella) to the shinbone (tibia). It occurs when the patellar tendon becomes inflamed or irritated, usually as a result of repetitive stress or sudden impact on the knee. Symptoms may include pain, swelling, and stiffness around the kneecap, and in some cases, a popping or snapping sensation may be felt when bending or extending the knee. Treatment typically involves rest, ice, compression, elevation (the RICE method), and physical therapy to help strengthen the affected tendon and promote healing. In severe cases, corticosteroid injections or surgery may be necessary.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:diaphragmatic_eventration rdfs:subClassOf :diaphragm_disease .
text: diaphragmatic eventration is a type of diaphragm disease.

Diaphragm disease can refer to a variety of conditions that affect the diaphragm, which is a muscle located in the chest and plays an essential role in breathing. Some common examples of diaphragm diseases include:

1. Diaphragmatic hernia - a condition where there is a weakening or tear in the diaphragm, allowing organs from the abdominal cavity to move into the chest.
2. Myasthenia gravis - an autoimmune disorder that affects the communication between nerves and muscles, including the diaphragm.
3. Polymyositis - a condition where multiple muscles, including the diaphragm, become weak due to inflammation.
4. Muscular dystrophy - a group of genetic muscle disorders that can affect the diaphragm and other muscles in the body.
5. Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) - a progressive lung disease that can affect the diaphragm's ability to function properly.

It is important to note that these are just some examples of diaphragm diseases and there may be other conditions that impact the muscle as well.

Esophageal atresia is a congenital birth defect that occurs when the esophagus doesn't develop properly. It can be diagnosed prenatally or after birth, and it requires surgery to repair. The condition has various synonyms, including Congenital atresia of esophagus, Congenital imperforate esophagus, Imperforate esophagus, Oesophageal atresia.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:intestinal_atresia rdfs:subClassOf :intestinal_disease .
text: intestinal atresia is a type of intestinal disease.

Hirschsprung disease, also known as aganglionic megacolon or congenital megacolon, is a type of intestinal obstruction that occurs due to a lack of normal ganglion cells in the muscles of the large intestine. This leads to an improper movement of the bowel and can cause severe constipation, abdominal pain, and other gastrointestinal symptoms.

Imperforate anus is a medical condition where the anus does not develop properly during fetal development. It results in a congenital absence of the anal opening, which can cause difficulties with bowel movements and other complications. The term "Congenital atresia of anus" refers specifically to this condition. Other synonyms for imperforate anus include "anal atresia" and "Congenital or infantile occlusion of anus."

Adrenal Cortical Hypofunction (ACH) is a medical condition where the adrenal cortex does not produce enough hormones. This can lead to a weakened immune system, low blood pressure, and difficulty responding to stress. It can be caused by genetic factors or autoimmune disorders. ACH can be diagnosed through blood tests that measure hormone levels, imaging studies (such as CT or MRI), and a history of symptoms such as fatigue, weakness, and low blood pressure. Treatment may include medication to replace the missing hormones, lifestyle changes, and monitoring of symptoms. It's important to work with a healthcare professional to manage this condition effectively.

Orbital granuloma is a type of chronic inflammation that occurs in the orbit or around the eyes. It typically affects individuals who have compromised immune systems, such as those with HIV/AIDS or cancer undergoing chemotherapy and radiation therapy. The exact cause of orbital granuloma is not yet fully understood, but it is believed to be related to a combination of genetic and environmental factors. Treatment options for orbital granuloma may include medications to reduce inflammation and prevent the growth of new blood vessels, as well as surgical interventions if the granuloma becomes too large or causes significant discomfort or vision problems. It is important to consult with an eye care professional if you suspect that you have orbital granuloma or any other eye-related condition.

Dressler's Syndrome, also known as Post-Myocardial Infarction Syndrome, is a type of pericarditis that occurs after a heart attack. It is characterized by inflammation in the pericardium, which is the sac-like structure surrounding the heart. This condition can cause chest pain and other symptoms similar to those of a traditional heart attack.

Malignant otitis externa is an aggressive form of otitis externa that has spread to the skull bone containing part of the ear canal, the middle ear, and the inner ear. It is commonly caused by the bacteria Pseudomonas, and can occur in individuals with weakened immune systems or older people with diabetes.

Beach ear, also known as acute otitis externa, is an inflammation of the outer ear caused by bacterial infection. It typically occurs after exposure to polluted water or trauma such as scratching the ear or inserting foreign objects into it. The symptoms include pain, discharge, and hearing loss. Treatment usually involves antibiotics and may also include steroids or other medications to help reduce inflammation and promote healing. Prevention measures can be taken by avoiding exposure to polluted water and practicing good hygiene habits.

Chronic fungal otitis externa, also known as chronic mycotic otitis externa, is a type of otomycosis that is persistent and long-lasting or recurrent. This condition is caused by an overgrowth of fungi in the external auditory canal, which can lead to inflammation, discharge, and hearing loss if left untreated. Treatment typically involves antifungal medications and surgery to remove infected tissue. It is important to seek medical attention for this condition to avoid further complications.

acute infection of pinna, also known as otitis externa, is a type of external ear infection. It can be caused by bacterial infections, and these infections are often related to underlying health problems or trauma. Common sources of trauma include ear piercing, boxing, blunt trauma, burns, bite wounds, and medical procedures. The most common bacterial pathogens that cause otitis externa are staphylococcal and streptococcal species.

double pterygium is a type of pterygium that has symptom loss of vision.
double pterygium is a type of something that at least disease has feature astigmatism.
double pterygium has definition A fleshy outpouching of conjunctival growth characterized by multiple heads or areas of bulk or origin, foreign body sensation, decreased vision, and astigmatism. Double pterygiums progress from pinguecula and are more common in people prone to ocular surface injury, such as those living in sunny, hot, and dry climates.

Conjunctival pterygium is a type of conjunctival disease that affects the conjunctiva, a thin transparent membrane that covers the inner surface of the eyeball and lines the outer surface of the eyelids. The condition is characterized by the growth of fleshy outpouchings or protrusions on the conjunctiva, which can cause symptoms such as foreign body sensation, decreased vision, and astigmatism. Conjunctival pterygium typically affects individuals who are prone to ocular surface injury, such as those living in sunny, hot, and dry climates. The condition progresses from a pinguecula, which is a less advanced form of conjunctival pterygium.

Viral pneumonia is an inflammatory illness of the lung that is commonly caused by various viruses such as influenza, parainfluenza, adenovirus, rhinovirus, and others. It is characterized by symptoms such as coughing, fever, chills, and shortness of breath, which can vary in severity from mild to life-threatening.
Viral pneumonia can be transmitted through respiratory droplets when an infected individual talks, sneezes or coughs, making it important for those who have contracted the virus to stay home and away from others until they are no longer contagious.
Treatment of viral pneumonia usually involves antiviral medications and supportive care such as oxygen therapy, fluid replacement, and pain relief. In some cases, hospitalization may be required, especially if the patient is experiencing severe symptoms or has underlying medical conditions that increase their risk of complications.

Stomach cancer, also known as gastric cancer, is a type of cancer that occurs in the stomach. It is a part of the gastrointestinal system and can be classified as a type of gastrointestinal system cancer. Stomach cancer can also be referred to as a stomach disease. The exact synonyms for stomach cancer are gastric cancer and gastric neoplasm.

That is correct, a malignant gastric granular cell tumor is a type of stomach cancer that originates in the cells lining the stomach. The tumor can be benign or malignant and can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, weight loss, and vomiting. It's also known as gastric granular cell tumor, gastric granuloma, or granular cell myofibroblastoma. It is important to note that not all benign tumors are cancerous, but a malignant tumor can grow and spread to other parts of the body. If you have any concerns about this type of tumor or if you are experiencing symptoms, it's best to consult with a medical professional.

gastric fundus cancer is a type of stomach cancer that occurs in the gastric fundus, which is the upper part of the stomach located between the esophagus and the cardia. The exact synonyms for gastric fundus cancer are "Ca fundus - stomach," "malignant neoplasm of the fundus of the stomach," and "malignant tumor of the fundus of the stomach."

Gastric lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the stomach, which is also known as gastritis. It is caused by an overproduction of abnormal white blood cells called lymphocytes in the digestive tract. This can lead to the growth of tumors or other abnormal tissue in the stomach. Gastric lymphoma is a type of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, which means it does not involve the Hodgkin's disease cell type. It is also known as gastrointestinal lymphoma or stomach lymphoma. The exact synonym for gastric lymphoma is Lymphoma of the stomach.

Microinvasive gastric cancer, also known as surface gastric cancer or early gastric cancer, is a type of gastric adenocarcinoma that has not penetrated deep into the stomach wall. It is characterized by the presence of cancer cells on the surface of the stomach and may also involve the lining of the stomach. This type of cancer is often treated with surgery, and in some cases, chemotherapy or radiation therapy may be recommended as well.

Pylorus cancer, also known as stomach cancer or gastric cancer, is a type of cancer that occurs in the pylorus region of the stomach. The pylorus is the area where the stomach connects to the small intestine and allows for the passage of food from the stomach into the small intestine.

Malignant neoplasm of the pylorus, also known as pylorus cancer or gastric cancer, is a malignant growth or tumor that forms in the cells of the pylorus region of the stomach. This type of cancer can spread to other parts of the body and may be life-threatening if not treated early. Symptoms of pylorus cancer may include abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, weight loss, and blood in the stool.

The treatment for pylorus cancer depends on the stage of the cancer and other factors such as age, overall health, and personal preferences. Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of these treatments. Early detection and regular screenings can help in detecting the cancer early and increase the chances of successful treatment.

Pyloric antrum cancer, also known as malignant neoplasm of the antrum of the stomach or malignant tumor of the pyloric antrum, is a type of gastric cancer that originates in the lining of the pyloric antrum, which is a part of the stomach located between the cardia and the body of the stomach. It is a relatively rare form of stomach cancer and can be difficult to diagnose due to its location deep within the stomach and the lack of specific symptoms associated with it. Treatment options may include surgical resection, chemotherapy, or radiation therapy.

Cardia cancer, also known as gastric cardia cancer, is a type of stomach cancer that occurs in the cardia region, which is the upper part of the stomach near the esophagus. It is characterized by the abnormal growth and spread of cells in the stomach lining, leading to the formation of tumors.

Cardia cancer can be difficult to diagnose due to its location deep within the stomach and the lack of specific symptoms. However, some common signs of cardia cancer may include heartburn, difficulty swallowing, abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting. If left untreated, cardia cancer can spread to other parts of the body and become life-threatening.

Treatment options for cardia cancer vary depending on the stage and extent of the disease. Common treatments include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and targeted therapy. It is essential to consult with a healthcare professional if you experience any symptoms or concerns about cardia cancer.

acute eustachian salpingitis is a medical condition that refers to the inflammation of the eustachian tubes, which connect the middle ear to the nasopharynx. It is also sometimes referred to as acute eustachian tube salpingitis. The term "salpingitis" specifically refers to the inflammation of the fallopian tubes, which are part of a woman's reproductive system. In this case, however, it seems that the term is being used to describe the inflammation of both the eustachian tubes and the fallopian tubes simultaneously. This condition can cause symptoms such as severe pain in the ear, difficulty hearing, dizziness, and fever. It is typically treated with antibiotics and pain relief medication. If left untreated, it can lead to more serious complications, such as mastoiditis or even meningitis.

Meningoencephalitis is a type of central nervous system disease that involves inflammation of the brain and spinal cord, along with inflammation of the meninges (the protective membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord). It can be caused by a variety of factors, such as viruses, bacteria, fungi, and parasites. Symptoms may include fever, headache, neck stiffness, confusion, seizures, and nausea. Treatment typically involves antibiotics, antivirals, or anti-fungal medications, depending on the cause of the infection. In some cases, corticosteroids may also be used to reduce inflammation.

Supine hypotensive syndrome is a type of vascular disease that occurs in late pregnancy and is characterized by severe supine hypotension. This condition can range from minimal cardiovascular alterations to severe shock, resulting from compression of the inferior vena cava by the gravid uterus. It is also known as antepartum maternal hypotension syndrome or postpartum maternal hypotension syndrome.

oculocerebrorenal syndrome is a type of x-linked recessive disease that has a material basis in mutation of the OCRL gene on chromosome Xq26. It is characterized by hydrophthalmia, cataract, mental retardation, vitamin D-resistant rickets, amino aciduria, and reduced ammonia production by the kidney. The syndrome has been named after Dr. Lowe, who first described it in 1937.

Late yaws is a type of yaws characterized by disabling consequences of the nose, bones, and palmar/plantar hyperkeratosis that appears after five years of the initial infection. It has been referred to as Gummata and ulcers due to yaws, gummatous frambesie, multiple papillomata due to yaws and wet crab yaws, and nodular late yaws.

early yaws is a type of yaws that results in initial papule at the site of entry of bacteria. Without treatment, this is followed by disseminated skin lesions over the body, bone pain and bone lesions may also occur. Early yaws has exact synonyms such as Frambesia, initial or primary, initial frambesial ulcer, initial lesions of yaws, bone and joint lesions due to yaws, bone and joint yaws lesion, chancre of yaws, and primary frambesia.

Osteomalacia is a type of bone remodeling disease.
Osteomalacia has definition A bone remodeling disease that results_from a vitamin D deficiency, leading to the softening of the bones..
Osteomalacia has exact match MESH:D010018.

text: calcium metabolism disease is a type of mineral metabolism disease.
Leukodystrophy is a type of cerebral degeneration that affects the white matter in the brain.

Metachromatic leukodystrophy is a type of sphingolipidosis, which is characterized by the accumulation of sulfatides in cells, particularly in the myelin-producing cells of the nervous system. It has several exact synonyms including MLD, Scholz cerebral sclerosis, arylsulfatase A deficiency, and deficiency of cerebroside-sulfatase, as well as sulfatide lipoidosis.

:refsum_disease rdfs:subClassOf :lipid_metabolism_disorder ;
    :has_definition "A lipid metabolic disorder that is characterized by a tetrad of clinical abnormalities: retinitis pigmentosa, peripheral neuropathy, cerebellar ataxia, and accumulation of an unusual branched-chain fatty acid, phytanic acid, in blood and tissues." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "Heredopathia atactica polyneuritiformis",
        "adult Refsum disease",
        "classic Refsum disease",
        "phytanic acid oxidase deficiency",
        "HMSN type IV"@en,
        "HSMN IV"@en,
        "Heredopathia atactica polyneuritiformis"@en,
        "Refsum's disease"@en .
text: refsum disease is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of fatty acids. It causes damage to the nerves and vision, as well as other neurological symptoms. The condition is passed down through families and can be diagnosed with a blood test that measures the levels of certain fatty acids. Treatment for refsum disease may include dietary changes, vitamin supplements, and medication to manage symptoms.

Retinitis pigmentosa is a type of retinal degeneration. This condition affects the photoreceptors or the retinal pigment epithelium of the retina, leading to progressive sight loss over time. It has an exact synonym of pericentral pigmentary retinopathy.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:krabbe_disease rdfs:subClassOf :sphingolipidosis ;
    :has_exact_synonym "Diffuse globoid body sclerosis"@en,
        "GLOBOID CELL LEUKOENCEPHALOPATHY"@en,
        "Galactosylceramide beta-galactosidase deficiency"@en,
        "Krabbe's disease"@en,
        "Krabbe's leukodystrophy"@en,
        "beta galactocerebrosidase deficiency"@en,
        "globoid cell leukodystrophy"@en .
text:
Krabbe disease is a type of sphingolipidosis, also known as globoid cell leukodystrophy. It is characterized by the accumulation of toxic compounds in the brain and spinal cord due to the deficiency of the enzyme beta-galactocerebrosidase. This leads to the progressive degeneration of myelin, which can result in severe neurological symptoms such as blindness, deafness, seizures, and developmental delays.
There are no specific treatments available for Krabbe disease, but research is ongoing to develop therapies that could potentially slow down or stop the progression of the disease. In some cases, bone marrow transplantation has been used as a treatment option, but it carries significant risks and is not widely available.
It's important for individuals with Krabbe disease to work closely with their healthcare providers to manage symptoms and improve quality of life. Early diagnosis and intervention can make a significant difference in the outcome for individuals with this condition.

Adrenoleukodystrophy is a type of leukodystrophy that is inherited in an X-linked recessive manner. It results in progressive brain damage, failure of the adrenal glands, and eventually death. The exact synonyms for this condition include ALD, Bronze Schilder disease, Encephalitis periaxialis concentrica, Siemerling-Creutzfeldt Disease, X-linked adrenoleukodystrophy, diffuse sclerosis, and sudanophilic cerebral sclerosis. It is also known as a type of leukodystrophy that disrupts the breakdown of very-long-chain fatty acids, resulting in brain damage.

intellectual disability is a type of specific developmental disorder.
intellectual disability has definition A developmental disorder that affects cognitive functioning and adaptive behavior, leading to significant limitations in both areas. It can impact an individual's ability to communicate, take care of themselves, and interact with others. Intellectual disability is often used as a synonym for mental retardation.

That is correct! Mild pre-eclampsia is a type of pre-eclampsia that is characterized by high blood pressure without evidence of damage to the organs. It occurs in women who were normotensive (had normal blood pressure) before 20 weeks of gestation. Is there anything else I can help you with?

:pre_eclampsia rdfs:subClassOf :hypertension ;
    :has_definition "A hypertension occurring during pregnancy characterized by large amounts of protein in the urine (proteinuria) and edema, usually by the last trimester of pregnancy." ;
    :has_exact_synonym "gestational hypertension"@en,
        "hypertension induced by pregnancy"@en,
        "pre-eclamptic toxaemia"@en,
        "preeclampsia"@en,
        "preeclampsia/eclampsia"@en,
        "pregnancy associated hypertension"@en,
        "pregnancy toxemia"@en,
        "proteinuric hypertension of pregnancy"@en,
        "toxaemia of pregnancy"@en .
text: Pre-eclampsia, also known as pregnancy-induced hypertension, is a condition characterized by high blood pressure during pregnancy. It is typically diagnosed after the 20th week of pregnancy and can cause proteinuria (large amounts of protein in the urine) and edema (swelling). Preeclampsia can be a serious condition if left untreated, but it can be managed with proper medical care.

fragment:
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .

:idiopathic_progressive_polyneuropathy rdfs:subClassOf :polyneuropathy .
text: idiopathic progressive polyneuropathy is a type of polyneuropathy.

CMT, or Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease, is a type of neuromuscular disorder that affects the peripheral nerves. It causes muscles in the arms, legs, hands, and feet to weaken over time, leading to a variety of symptoms such as numbness, tingling, and muscle atrophy. There are several subtypes of CMT, which are characterized by different patterns of inheritance and clinical features. Treatment for CMT often focuses on managing symptoms and improving quality of life through physical therapy, medications, and other interventions.

Pleural tuberculosis is a type of extrapulmonary tuberculosis that results in lymphocyte-predominant exudative pleural effusion, located in the pleura. This occurs as a result of an allergic response to tuberculoprotein causing the permeability of the pleural vasculature to alter, leading to a sub-pleural caseous focus rupture into the pleural sac. It is also known as Pearly disease, Tuberculosis of pleura, Tuberculous pleurisy, and Tuberculous pleuritis. In primary progressive tuberculosis, it may be referred to as tuberculous pleurisy.

Hartnup disease is a rare genetic disorder that affects the metabolism of amino acids. It is characterized by aminoaciduria, which involves excessive urination of amino acids, particularly monocarboxylic monoamines and neutral amino acids. The disease also causes a dry, red, scaly rash on the skin and muscle coordination problems, especially affecting the cerebellum. It is caused by mutations in the SLC26A3 gene, which encodes for a protein involved in the transport of these amino acids across cell membranes.

Chronic tic disorder is a type of neurological disorder that is characterized by the presence of recurring, involuntary movements or sounds known as tics. These tics can range from mild to severe and may affect various parts of the body, including the face, neck, arms, legs, and vocal cords. Chronic tic disorder can cause significant distress and impairment in daily functioning, and is often treated with medications or other therapies. It is important to seek medical advice if you or someone you know is experiencing symptoms of chronic tic disorder.

Glucose intolerance is a condition in which the body has difficulty regulating blood sugar levels. This can lead to hyperglycemia, which can cause symptoms like increased thirst and frequent urination. In some cases, it may also be caused by malabsorption of glucose, where the body is unable to properly absorb sugar from the diet. It's important to manage this condition through a proper diet and exercise to maintain healthy blood sugar levels.

Lactose intolerance is a common food disorder that affects many people, especially those from certain ethnic groups. It occurs when the body is unable to digest lactose, a sugar found in milk and other dairy products. Symptoms of lactose intolerance can include bloating, cramping, diarrhea, and nausea. Treatment typically involves avoiding or limiting the consumption of dairy products and taking enzymes that aid in digestion. In some cases, a medical professional may recommend a lactose-free diet as well. It's important to note that while it is safe for most people with lactose intolerance to consume small amounts of lactose, it is best to consult with a doctor before making any changes to your diet.

acquired short bowel syndrome is a type of intestinal disease.
acquired short bowel syndrome has definition An intestinal disease that occurs as a result of a surgical procedure or medical condition that causes a reduction in the length of the small and/or large intestine, leading to difficulty in absorbing nutrients.
acquired short bowel syndrome has exact synonym acquired short gut syndrome.

Blind loop syndrome, also known as bacterial overgrowth syndrome, is a type of intestinal disease characterized by an imbalance in the bacteria present in the small intestine. This can lead to disruptions in the normal digestion and absorption processes. It is important to address this issue through proper diet and antibiotic treatment when necessary.

Tropical sprue, also known as tropical enteropathy or tropical sprue enteropathy, is a type of intestinal disease characterized by inflammation and damage to the small intestine. The condition can cause malabsorption of nutrients, leading to symptoms such as diarrhea, vomiting, abdominal pain, weight loss, and fatigue. Tropical sprue is more commonly seen in tropical and subtropical regions and can be caused by a variety of factors including bacterial, viral, or parasitic infections, as well as autoimmune disorders. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you may have tropical sprue in order to receive an accurate diagnosis and appropriate treatment.

Celiac disease is a type of autoimmune disorder that affects the small intestine. It occurs when the body's immune system mistakenly attacks the lining of the small intestine, causing inflammation and damage to the digestive enzymes. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, diarrhea, constipation, nausea, vomiting, and loss of appetite. The condition is often triggered by gluten consumption and can be managed through a strict adherence to a gluten-free diet. Celiac disease is also associated with the HLA-DQ gene and can lead to complications if left untreated.

Rickets is a type of bone remodeling disease that occurs when there is an impairment in the mineralization or calcification of bones before epiphyseal closure due to deficiency or impaired metabolism of vitamin D, phosphorus, or calcium. This results in softening and deformity located in the bone.

Pancreatic steatorrhea, also known as pancreatic steatorrhoea, is a condition in which the pancreas produces excessive amounts of fatty, sticky secretions. This can lead to problems such as abdominal pain, weight loss, and poor digestion. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you may have this condition, as it can be caused by various underlying health issues and requires proper diagnosis and treatment.

Protein losing enteropathy, also known as exudative enteropathy, is a type of intestinal disease characterized by the loss of protein from the body through the gastrointestinal tract. It can be caused by a variety of factors, such as infections, inflammation, and certain medications. Symptoms may include abdominal pain, diarrhea, vomiting, and weight loss. Treatment typically involves addressing the underlying cause, nutritional support, and medications to manage symptoms.
allergic urticaria is a type of skin rash caused by an allergic reaction.

Acute gonococcal cervicitis is a type of acute cervicitis that occurs as a result of infection by the bacterium Neisseria gonorrhoeae. It causes inflammation and tenderness in the cervical region, often accompanied by discharge and pain during sexual intercourse. This condition requires treatment with antibiotics to prevent complications such as pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) or infertility.

Acute cervicitis is a type of cervicitis that refers to inflammation or irritation in the cervix. It usually develops within one to three days after sexual intercourse and can cause symptoms such as abnormal vaginal bleeding, discharge, and mild to moderate pain. However, it's important to note that not all cases of acute cervicitis are caused by sexual activity, and other possible causes include infections or irritants.

Lymph node cancer, also known as lymphoma, is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system. The lymphatic system is part of the immune system and helps to filter out harmful substances from the blood, produces and stores white blood cells, and transports them throughout the body. Lymph node cancer can occur in various parts of the body, including the neck, chest, abdomen, and pelvis, among others. It is important to note that lymphoma is not the same as leukemia, which affects the blood cells rather than the lymphatic system.

Fanconi Syndrome is a renal tubular transport disease characterized by glucosuria, phosphaturia, generalized aminoaciduria and HCO3 wasting. It has exact synonyms such as Congenital Fanconi Syndrome, De Toni-Fanconi syndrome, Fanconi-de Toni syndrome, Infantile nephropathic cystinosis, Lignac-Fanconi syndrome and adult Fanconi Anemia or adult Fanconi syndrome. It is also known as deToni Fanconi syndrome.

Microphthalmia is a condition in which one or both of the eyes are significantly smaller than normal. It can be caused by genetic factors, trauma, or other conditions that affect eye development. In some cases, microphthalmia may not cause any symptoms and may only be discovered during an eye examination. However, in more severe cases, it can lead to vision problems and other complications. Treatment options depend on the underlying cause but may include glasses, contact lenses, or surgery to correct the issue. It's important to consult with a healthcare professional if you suspect you or a loved one may have microphthalmia.

Interstitial nephritis refers to inflammation and damage of the interstitial tissue in the kidney, which can lead to a decline in renal function. Renal tubulo-interstitial disease (TID) specifically affects the renal tubules and interstitium. It is important to differentiate between these two types of nephritis as treatment strategies may differ based on the specific location and type of damage.

Wolfram syndrome, also known as WFS (Wolfram Syndrome), is a rare genetic disorder that affects multiple systems in the body. It is characterized by diabetes mellitus (high blood sugar levels), optic atrophy (progressive vision loss), and deafness. The exact synonym of Wolfram syndrome is WS.

cystinosis is a type of lysosomal storage disease characterized by the abnormal accumulation of cystine in the lysosomes, which follows an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern and has a material basis in mutations in the CTNS gene located on chromosome 17. It is also known as cystine storage disease.

Schizotypal personality disorder is a type of psychiatric disorder characterized by an individual's pattern of behavior, cognition, and inner experience that deviates from what is considered to be "normal" or mainstream. People with schizotypal personality disorder may have difficulty in social situations, show odd behaviors and thinking, and often have unconventional beliefs. It's important to note that while these individuals may not suffer from a full-blown psychotic episode, they can still experience significant distress and impairment in their daily lives.
