text: cholecystolithiasis is a type of gallbladder disease.

Miliaria rubra, also known as prickly heat, is a type of miliaria characterized by the presence of erythematous papules that leak sweat into the deeper, subcorneal layers of the epidermis. This leads to a local inflammatory reaction and can cause discomfort or irritation. Miliaria rubra is commonly seen in hot and humid environments, where excessive sweating occurs. It is also more common in young children due to their thinner skin.

Hypohidrosis is a condition where the body is unable to sweat properly. This can cause problems with temperature regulation, leading to symptoms such as excessive heat and dry skin. It can be caused by damage to the sweat glands or other medical conditions that affect the ability of the body to regulate its temperature. Treatment may involve medications or other therapies to help improve sweating and cooling capabilities.

Anhidrosis is a medical condition where the body is unable to sweat, resulting in symptoms such as excessive heat and dry skin. It can be caused by various factors, including genetic disorders, injuries, or certain medications. Treatment may involve using artificial sweat glands, medications, or other therapies to help the body produce sweat again.

pertussis is a type of commensal bacterial infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the respiratory tract. It has a material basis in either Bordetella pertussis or Bordetella parapertussis, which produce toxins that paralyze the cilia of the respiratory epithelial cells. The infection is characterized by a prolonged, high-pitched, deeply indrawn breath (whoop). It is also known as whooping cough.

Neonatal respiratory failure is a type of respiratory failure that occurs in newborn infants, typically within the first 24 hours of life. It occurs when the neonate is unable to breathe adequately, leading to insufficient oxygen intake and potentially causing harm or even death if left untreated.

Respiratory failure is a medical condition where the lungs are unable to provide enough oxygen to the body. This can be caused by various factors, such as injury, infection, or disease of the respiratory system. It is often characterized by shortness of breath and difficulty in breathing. Treatment for respiratory failure depends on the underlying cause but may include oxygen therapy, medications, and other interventions to help improve lung function.

Yes, that is correct. Band-shaped keratopathy is another term for band keratopathy, which refers to a specific type of corneal degeneration characterized by the formation of a crescent-shaped lesion or "band" in the cornea. This condition can cause visual disturbances and may require treatment to prevent further damage to the eye.

Common warts are caused by the human papillomavirus (HPV). They can appear on any part of your body, but they're most common on your hands and fingers. Common warts look like a small, rough, raised area of skin with a visible surface. They can be painful or itchy, and they may grow to several inches in size.

Common warts are usually harmless, but they can be treated to prevent them from spreading or becoming more difficult to treat. Treatment options include over-the-counter creams and gels containing salicylic acid or other common wart-removing chemicals, as well as prescription medications like imiquimod or podophyllotoxin. If the wart is too large or located in a hard-to-reach area, your doctor may recommend a different treatment approach, such as freezing the wart with liquid nitrogen or surgically removing it.

It's important to practice good hygiene and avoid touching or shaking hands to prevent the spread of common warts. If you have a common wart, it's a good idea to keep it covered when you're not treating it to prevent its spread to others.

human papillomavirus infectious disease is a type of viral infectious disease that has_material_basis_in human papillomaviruses, which establish productive infections only in the stratified epithelium of the skin or mucous membranes. These viruses cause warts and sometimes tumors. They are transmitted by sexual contact.
human papillomavirus infectious disease is also known as HPV.

Anogenital venereal wart is a type of viral infectious disease that results from infection located in the skin of the vagina, cervix, uterus, anus, penis, scrotum, mouth or throat. It has a material basis in human papillomaviruses (types 6 and 11) which are transmitted by direct contact with the skin during oral, genital, or anal sex with an infected partner. The infection has symptoms of anogenital warts.
It is also known as Anogenital Human Papilloma Virus Infectious Disease, Anogenital warts, Genital warts, and Venereal wart. It can be related to Condyloma acuminatum.

Total internal ophthalmoplegia is a condition in which the muscles that control eye movements are paralyzed. This can cause difficulty with eye alignment, focusing, and other visual functions. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you or someone else may have this condition.

That's correct! Non-suppurative otitis media is a type of middle ear infection that does not involve pus or purulent discharge. Instead, it involves the inflammation and swelling of the middle ear due to various factors such as allergies, infections, or even certain medications. It's also sometimes referred to as "otitis media with effusion" (OME) when there is a buildup of fluid in the middle ear without any signs of inflammation.
Non-suppurative otitis media, or glue ear, is a condition in which the middle ear fills with fluid that becomes thick and glue-like. This can lead to conductive hearing impairment.

Allescheriosis is a type of primary systemic mycosis, characterized by the development of abscesses. It has a material basis in the fungus Pseudallescheria boydii and can result in systemic fungal infection. The exact synonym for Allescheriosis is Petriellidosis.

Pseudomembranous conjunctivitis is a type of acute conjunctivitis that involves the formation of a fibrin-rich exudate on the surface of the conjunctiva. It can be caused by various infectious agents such as Corynebacterium diphtheriae, streptococci, pneumococci, herpes simplex virus, adenovirus, Chlamydia and gonococci, as well as chemical irritants, erythema multiforme, and ocular pemphigoid.

Syndactyly is a condition where two or more digits on a hand are fused together. It can be caused by genetic factors, and it is sometimes associated with certain chromosomal abnormalities. The term "webbing of digits" is also used to describe this condition.
acute laryngopharyngitis is a type of upper respiratory tract disease that involves inflammation of the larynx and pharynx.

Serous conjunctivitis, except viral is a type of acute conjunctivitis that is characterized by inflammation of the conjunctiva and a serous discharge. It is not caused by viruses, but rather by other means such as allergies or irritants.

Di George Syndrome (DGS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects approximately 1 in every 4,000 live births. It is characterized by a large deletion of the chromosome 22q11.2 region which includes the DGS gene needed for development of the thymus and related glands with subsequent lack of T-cell production. The exact synonyms for this condition include: 22q11.2 deletion syndrome, DiGeorge sequence, and Pharyngeal pouch syndrome.

hypoparathyroidism is a medical condition in which one or more of the four parathyroid glands are underactive. This results in low levels of parathyroid hormone (PTH) being produced, which can lead to abnormal calcium levels in the blood. It is also known as secondary hyperparathyroidism.

Esophageal varix is a condition where the veins in the esophagus become inflamed and enlarged. It can cause difficulty swallowing, chest pain, and regurgitation. Esophageal varix is a type of esophageal disease and it has exact synonyms like "Bleeding esophageal varices" or "esophageal varices in disease classified elsewhere with bleeding." It's also possible to use "esophageal varix without mentioning bleeding."
T cell deficiency is a type of primary immunodeficiency disease. A primary immunodeficiency disease that is characterized by decreased numbers of circulating or functioning T cells.

Parathyroid gland disease, also known as hyperparathyroidism, is a medical condition caused by an overactive parathyroid gland. The four main types of hyperparathyroidism are:

1. Primary Hyperparathyroidism - This occurs when one or more of the four parathyroid glands become overactive and produce too much calcium.
2. Secondary Hyperparathyroidism - This type is caused by another underlying medical condition, such as kidney disease or an overactive thyroid gland (hyperthyroidism).
3. Tertiary Hyperparathyroidism - This occurs when the body has too much calcium due to cancer that has spread to the bones or other organs.
4. Constitutional Hyperparathyroidism - This type is caused by an inherited genetic condition that leads to an increased risk of developing parathyroid gland disease.

Parathyroid gland disease can lead to various symptoms, including:

1. Fatigue and weakness
2. Bone pain or tenderness
3. Nausea or vomiting
4. Muscle cramps or spasms
5. Increased thirst or urination
6. Swollen or enlarged parathyroid glands (located in the neck)

Treatment for parathyroid gland disease depends on the severity of the condition and may include:

1. Medications to control calcium levels in the blood
2. Surgery to remove one or more of the overactive parathyroid glands
3. Radiation therapy (in rare cases)

It is important to consult a medical professional if you experience any symptoms of parathyroid gland disease, as prompt treatment can help alleviate symptoms and prevent complications.

Primary hyperparathyroidism is a type of hyperparathyroidism that is characterized by an overproduction of parathyroid hormone and elevated levels of calcium in the blood. Familial primary hyperparathyroidism refers to a specific case of primary hyperparathyroidism that has been passed down through generations of a family.

Angelucci's syndrome, also known as acute atopic conjunctivitis, is a type of allergic conjunctivitis. It is characterized by inflammation and redness of the eyes, often accompanied by itching and discharge. The condition is caused by an overreaction of the body's immune system to allergens present in the environment. Treatment typically includes the use of eye drops to reduce inflammation and allergic symptoms. Prevention measures such as avoiding contact with allergens and using protective eyewear can also help manage the condition.

allergic conjunctivitis is a type of allergic disease characterized by symptoms such as red, itchy, and watery eyes resulting from exposure to an allergen or irritant. It is considered a chronic form of conjunctivitis and can be caused by sensitization to allergens found in the environment.
Opioid abuse is a type of substance abuse that involves the recurring use of opioid drugs despite negative consequences.

Buphthalmos is a type of hydrophthalmos, which refers to a condition characterized by early onset glaucoma in one or both eyes with elevated intraocular pressure, increased corneal diameter, and swelling of the globe. Symptoms of buphthalmos can include early vision loss, photophobia, blepharospasm, tearing, increased corneal diameter, increased corneal thickness, and enlarged globe. Buphthalmos is caused by severe congenital defects of the trabecular meshwork and anterior chamber angle that block aqueous outflow and raise intraocular pressure, leading to optic nerve atrophy and early vision loss. It is also known as primary congenital glaucoma 3A and simple buphthalmos.

Hydrophthalmos is a type of primary congenital glaucoma, which is characterized by early onset glaucoma in one or both eyes with elevated intraocular pressure and increased corneal diameter. It is caused by congenital defects of the trabecular meshwork and anterior chamber angle that block aqueous outflow and raise intraocular pressure, leading to optic nerve atrophy and early vision loss.

Acute contagious conjunctivitis is a type of acute conjunctivitis, which is characterized by highly contagious conjunctival hyperemia and mucopurulent discharge and has material basis in Hemophilius Aegypticus. It can also be referred to as contagious opthalmia or pinkeye.

text: chronic tympanitis is a type of tympanic membrane disease.

Conjunctival folliculosis is a type of acute conjunctivitis characterized by the inflammation and hypertrophy of the conjunctiva, specifically involving the tissue that lines the eyelids. The condition can cause discomfort, redness, and increased tear production. It is typically caused by an allergic reaction to pollen or other irritants, but can also be caused by viruses or bacteria. Treatment usually involves using eye drops to reduce inflammation and allergens, as well as avoiding exposure to irritants that may worsen the condition.

Small intestine diverticulitis is a condition where small pouches form in the wall of the small intestine. It is also sometimes referred to as Diverticulosis of the small intestine with hemorrhage. It can cause symptoms such as abdominal pain, constipation, and blood in the stool. It's important to consult a medical professional if you experience these symptoms.

Acute hemorrhagic conjunctivitis is a type of viral infectious disease that results in inflammation located in the conjunctiva. It has a material basis in either Human coxsackievirus A24 or Human enterovirus 70, which are transmitted by contaminated fomites or through contact with contaminated hands. The symptoms include vascular dilation, eyelid edema, photophobia, redness of the eyes, watering of the eye, conjunctival congestion, and superficial punctate epithelial keratitis. Acute hemorrhagic conjunctivitis is also known as Apollo disease and Epidemic hemorrhagic conjunctivitis.

Spondyloarthropathy is a type of arthropathy that affects the spine and sacroiliac joint, as well as other peripheral joints. It is characterized by inflammation and pain in these joints, and can lead to long-term damage if left untreated. The exact synonym for spondyloarthropathy is spondylarthrosis, which refers specifically to the degenerative form of the disease. Other terms that may be used to describe this condition include ankylosing spondylitis and reactive arthritis.

Acute orbital inflammation, also known as acute inflammation of the orbit, is a type of orbital disease characterized by the inflammation of the tissues surrounding the eyes. Symptoms may include pain, swelling, and redness around the eyes, as well as vision changes or difficulty moving the eyes. Treatment typically involves anti-inflammatory medications and rest, and in severe cases, steroids may be administered. It is important to consult an eye doctor if you suspect you have acute orbital inflammation.

orbital periostitis is a type of acute orbital inflammation.
orbital periostitis is an inflammation that affects the bones and tissues surrounding the eyes.
orbital periostitis has symptoms such as pain, redness, and swelling around the eyes. It can cause double vision and be a sign of a fracture or dislocation in the orbit.

orbital osteomyelitis is an inflammation of the bones in the orbit (eye socket), which is the area around the eye. It can cause significant pain and discomfort, and if left untreated, it can lead to long-term damage or even blindness. The condition usually begins with an infection in one of the sinuses, which then spreads to the bones in the orbit. Treatment typically involves antibiotics, steroids, and sometimes surgery to remove infected or damaged bone.

Orbital tenonitis is a type of acute inflammation that affects the soft tissue surrounding the eye, specifically in the orbit or bony socket where the eyeball sits. It can cause symptoms such as pain, swelling, redness, and decreased vision. Treatment usually involves corticosteroid medications to reduce inflammation and alleviate pain, along with other measures to manage the condition.

orbital cellulitis is a type of acute orbital inflammation that can cause painful swelling around the eye and other symptoms such as double vision, drooping eyelids, headache, fever, and blurry vision. It's important to seek medical attention if you suspect you have this condition.

Adhesive otitis media is a type of auditory system disease characterized by the thin, retracted eardrum becoming stuck to the bones and ossicles within the middle ear. It is also known as chronic adhesive otitis media.

Appendix cancer, also known as appendiceal cancer or carcinoid of the appendix, is a rare type of intestinal cancer that originates in the appendix. It can affect any part of the appendix, including its lining (mucosa), and may spread to other parts of the body if not diagnosed and treated early. Appendiceal cancer has a definition as an intestinal cancer that is located in the appendix. Some common symptoms of appendiceal cancer include abdominal pain, constipation, and diarrhea. If you are experiencing any of these symptoms or suspect you may have appendiceal cancer, it's important to seek medical attention right away. Early diagnosis and treatment can increase the chances of a successful recovery.
Appendiceal neoplasm refers to a benign tumor that develops in the appendix. It can also be referred to as appendix neoplasm or neoplasm of the appendix.

Appendiceal Lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the lymph tissue in the appendix, also known as mucosal-associated lymphoid tissue (MALT). It typically occurs when a person has an inflammation or swelling of the mucosa, which is the inner lining of the digestive tract. This condition can cause the abnormal proliferation and accumulation of malignant lymphocytes in the appendix. Appendiceal Lymphoma can be classified into two main types: extranodal (which involves the non-nodal areas of the body) and nodal (which affects the lymph nodes). Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, chemotherapy, or a combination of these treatments. In some cases, observation alone may be recommended for people with early stage disease that is slow-growing and not causing any symptoms.

Neonatal polycythemia is a condition that occurs when there are too many red blood cells in an infant's blood. It is also known as erythroblastosis foetalis or hydrops fetalis. This can be caused by a genetic disorder, such as sickle cell disease, or other medical conditions, such as heart problems or infections. It is important to receive proper treatment for neonatal polycythemia to prevent complications and ensure the health of the infant.

Neonatal anemia is a condition where a newborn baby has a low amount of red blood cells or hemoglobin, which is necessary for transporting oxygen throughout the body. It can be caused by a variety of factors such as genetic disorders, infections, and complications during delivery. Treatment usually involves administering blood transfusions to increase the baby's red blood cell count. It is important to identify and treat neonatal anemia early on to prevent long-term health problems for the baby.

Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) is a rare but serious condition that occurs when small blood clots form throughout the body, obstructing blood vessels and interfering with blood flow. It can occur in newborns as well as adults. DIC in newborns can be caused by a variety of factors, including infections, trauma, or complications during delivery. Symptoms may include fever, reduced urine output, jaundice, and decreased activity. Treatment typically involves supportive care, such as blood transfusions and medications to help dissolve the clots. In severe cases, mechanical circulatory support may be necessary. It's important to note that DIC can be a complication of other medical conditions or injuries, so it's crucial to work with a healthcare provider to identify and address any underlying issues.

Disseminated intravascular coagulation (DIC) is a type of thrombophilia that occurs when there is widespread clotting within the blood vessels. It is also known as Defibrination syndrome and Diffuse or disseminated intravascular coagulation.

Vitamin K Deficiency Bleeding is a condition where an individual lacks the essential nutrient vitamin K, which leads to difficulties in blood clot formation and subsequently results in bleeding. It can occur due to various reasons such as liver prematurity, lack of vitamin K in breast milk diet, malabsorption, chronic illness, or certain medications. Symptoms may include easy bruising, bleeding gums, excessive menstrual bleeding, and blood in the urine. Treatment typically involves increasing vitamin K intake through food sources like leafy greens, broccoli, spinach, and kale, or supplements if needed. In severe cases, vitamin K injections may be required to replenish the nutrient levels quickly.

Brill-Zinsser disease, also known as recrudescent typhus or relapsing typhus fever, is a mild form of epidemic typhus that can return after a long period of latency due to immunosuppression, malnutrition, or other illnesses. It was first described by Dr. Hans Zinsser in 1920. The disease is characterized by fever, headache, and chills, and is spread through the bites of infected body lice. Prevention measures include avoiding contact with infected individuals, using insecticides to control lice populations, and practicing good hygiene. Treatment typically involves antibiotics to combat the bacteria that cause the disease.

text: Typhus is a bacterial disease that is transmitted through the bites of infected lice or fleas. It can cause fever, rash, and other symptoms. There are several different types of typhoid fever, including epidemic (louse-borne) typhus, endemic flea-borne typhus, and murine (endemic) typhus. Each type is caused by a different strain of the Rickettsia bacteria.

You are correct. Social phobia, also known as social anxiety disorder, is a type of phobic disorder characterized by extreme and persistent fear or anxiety in social situations. These situations can include public speaking, meeting new people, or being in crowded places. The fear is often irrational, but it can be debilitating for those who suffer from it. It is estimated that about 7% of the population will experience social phobia at some point in their lives, and women are more likely to develop the condition than men. Treatment options include therapy, medication, and self-help strategies.
Cat scratch disease, also known as debre's syndrome and foshay-mollaret cat
Lyssa is an exact synonym of rabies.

ornithosis is a type of primary bacterial infectious disease that results in systemic infection, has material basis in Chlamydia psittaci, which is transmitted by inhaling aerosolized dried droppings or through contact with infected birds. The symptoms include fever, headache, rash, chills and pneumonia. It is also known as psittacosis.

Chlamydia is a sexually transmitted infection caused by the bacterium Chlamydia trachomatis. It can also be transmitted through non-sexual means, such as during childbirth or from mother to baby. The symptoms of chlamydia include discharge from the penis, burning during urination, and abnormal vaginal bleeding in women. If left untreated, Chlamydia can lead to complications such as pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) in women and epididymitis in men. It is important to practice safe sex and get tested regularly if you are sexually active.

Trachoma is a type of commensal bacterial infectious disease that results in an infection located in the eye. It has a material basis in Chlamydia trachomatis (A, B, Ba and C serovars). Trachoma can be transmitted by contact with eye discharge from the infected person or through congenital transmission. The infection causes the eyelid to turn inward, which makes eyelashes scratch the cornea.

Hantavirus hemorrhagic fever with renal syndrome is a type of viral infectious disease that affects the kidneys and is caused by Orthohantavirus dobravaense, Orthohantavirus hantanense, Orthohantavirus puumalaense, or Orthohantavirus seoulense. It can cause symptoms such as headache, fever, muscle pain, facial flush, petechiae, proteinuria, and renal failure. The disease is also known by the exact synonyms HFRS, Hemorrhagic fever, Russian, Hemorrhagic nephrosonephritis, and Puumala virus nephropathy. It is transmitted by rodents and can be carried by them without causing symptoms.

Plummer's disease, also known as toxic nodular goiter, is a type of hyperthyroidism that occurs when the thyroid gland becomes inflamed and produces too much thyroid hormone. It is caused by an excessive intake of iodine, which can lead to the formation of large, solid nodules in the gland. Symptoms of Plummer's disease include weight loss, increased heart rate, tremors, and heat intolerance. Treatment typically involves medications to control hormone levels and reduce inflammation, as well as surgery to remove the affected thyroid tissue.

Solar retinopathy, also known as solar retinitis, is a condition in which the retina is damaged by excessive exposure to ultraviolet (UV) radiation from the sun. This damage can cause scar tissue to form on the retina and may lead to vision loss if left untreated. It is important to protect your eyes from UV radiation by wearing appropriate eye protection, such as sunglasses and a hat with a broad brim, and limiting your exposure to direct sunlight. If you suspect you have solar retinopathy or are experiencing vision loss, it is important to seek medical attention as soon as possible.

Tick paralysis is a condition characterized by an acute, ascending, flaccid motor paralysis caused by the introduction of a neurotoxin into humans during attachment and feeding by several tick species such as Dermacentor andersoni, Dermacentor variabilis, Amblyomma americanum, Amblyomma maculatum, Ixodes scapularis, Ixodes pacificus, Ixodes holocyclus, Rhipicephalus sanguineus and Otobius megnini. The symptoms include local inflammation, edema and hemorrhage.

Ventilation pneumonitis is a type of extrinsic allergic alveolitis. It's caused by inhalation of antigens from thermophilic actinomycetes species growing in air conditioners and humidifiers. Fungi like Aureobasidium sp and Candida albicans that survive in the contaminated water in humidifiers and air conditioners can also cause the disease. The disease is also known as Air-conditioner and humidifier lung, and Humidifier lung.

arteriovenous malformation is a type of hemangioma that is characterized by a configuration of blood vessels that shunts arterial blood directly into veins by bypassing the capillary system. It is also known as an arteriovenous hemangioma, cirsoid aneurysm, racemose angioma, and racemose hemangioma.

Vertebral artery occlusion is a type of artery disease that occurs when the vertebral artery, which supplies blood to the brain, becomes blocked. This can lead to a stroke or other serious neurological complications. It is also known as Occlusion and stenosis of the vertebral artery.

Correct, pituitary infarction is a type of necrosis that occurs when the blood supply to the pituitary gland is disrupted. This can lead to damage or even death of cells in the gland and can result in hormonal imbalances or other health problems. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect you may have experienced a pituitary infarction.

cercarial dermatitis is a type of skin disease.
cercarial dermatitis is characterized by the short-term, cutaneous inflammatory response associated with penetration of the skin by cercariae of bird schistosome, Austrobilharzia variglandis. It causes symptoms such as skin reddening, itching, and the appearance of itchy, raised papules that occur within hours of infection. The disease is also known as cutaneous schistosomiasis or sea bather's eruption.

Mobitz II atrioventricular block, also known as second degree heart block, is a type of cardiac conduction disorder. It occurs when the signal from the sinus node in the upper chamber (atrium) of the heart is delayed or blocked, causing it to beat too slowly. This condition can be caused by a variety of factors such as damage to the heart muscle, medications, and electrolyte imbalances.
Mobitz II atrioventricular block can lead to symptoms such as dizziness, lightheadedness, palpitations, and fatigue. It is typically diagnosed through a combination of physical examination, EKG testing, and cardiac monitoring. Treatment options may include medication, pacemaker implantation, or lifestyle changes to manage symptoms and prevent complications.

African histoplasmosis is a type of Histoplasma capsulatum var duboisii, which causes systemic fungal infection. This condition is transmitted through airborne spores and results in the formation of nodules, ulcers, and osteolytic bone lesions.

Histoplasmosis with retinitis is a type of retinitis caused by the fungus Histoplasma capsulatum. It can cause inflammation and damage to the retina, which may lead to vision loss if left untreated. Symptoms include blurry or distorted vision, floaters, pain or pressure in the eye, and sensitivity to light. Diagnosis typically involves a combination of medical history, physical examination, and diagnostic tests such as imaging and cultures. Treatment options may include antifungal medications, corticosteroids, and surgery in severe cases. It's important to seek medical attention if you experience any of these symptoms to prevent further damage and preserve your vision.

Kyasanur forest disease is a type of viral infectious disease that has material basis in the Kyasanur Forest Disease virus, which is transmitted by Haemaphysalis spinigera tick bite. Symptoms include fever, headache, stiff neck, severe muscle pain, cough, dehydration, and bleeding problems.

Schizophreniform disorder is a type of psychotic disorder that is characterized by symptoms similar to those of schizophrenia, but the duration of these symptoms needs to be present for at least one month.

Ainhum is a connective tissue disease that results in increasing fibrous constriction and ultimately in spontaneous amputation of the toes, with a painful constriction of the base of the fifth toe being followed by bilateral spontaneous amputation (autoamputation) a few years later. It is also known as dactylolysis spontanea. The exact synonym for Ainhum is MESH:D000387.

sarcoidosis is a type of disease that affects the organs in the body. It is caused by an overreaction of the immune system, which can lead to the growth of granulomas (collections of inflammatory cells) in various organs and tissues. The exact cause of sarcoidosis is not known, but it is thought to be triggered by exposure to certain environmental factors or infectious agents. It can affect any organ in the body, but is most commonly found in the lungs, skin, eyes, and lymph glands.

Rhinoscleroma is a bacterial infection that affects the mucous membranes lining the nose, throat, and airways. It is caused by the bacterium Klebsiella rhinoscleromatis. The symptoms of rhinoscleroma include nasal congestion, discharge, fever, sore throat, cough, and difficulty swallowing. Treatment typically involves antibiotics, such as amoxicillin or gentamicin, to kill the bacteria causing the infection. In some cases, surgery may be needed to remove infected tissue.

Lemierre's syndrome, also known as postanginal sepsis or human necrobacillosis, is a bacterial infection caused by the Fusobacterium necrophorum bacteria. It typically starts with a severe throat infection, often presenting as tonsillitis or pharyngitis, accompanied by fever, chills, and leukocytosis (an increase in white blood cells). The disease progresses to the formation of ulcerative or necrotic lesions, and multisystem abscesses can form. Lemierre's syndrome is a serious condition that requires prompt treatment with antibiotics and supportive care.

Tetanus is a bacterial infection caused by the Clostridium tetani bacteria. It results in the prolonged contraction of skeletal muscle fibers and can be life-threatening if left untreated. The symptoms of tetanus include stiffness of the jaw, difficulty swallowing, muscle spasms, and seizures. Tetanus is typically treated with antitoxin and tetanus toxoid vaccine, which help neutralize the toxins produced by the bacteria and boost the immune system's response to future infections.

Pneumocystosis is a type of opportunistic mycosis, which means that it only occurs in individuals with weakened immune systems. It can affect various organs and tissues throughout the body, including the lungs, eyes, ears, skin, thyroid, pituitary, palate, parathyroid, esophagus, pleura, heart, liver, spleen, small intestine, adrenals, kidneys, bone marrow, and lymph nodes. It is caused by the fungus Pneumocystis jirovecii, which affects interstitial and alveolar tissues in the lungs.

Symptoms of pneumocystosis may include fever, cough, shortness of breath, and non-productive (dry) cough. If left untreated, it can lead to serious complications such as respiratory failure and death. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial to prevent these complications.

text: Gingival recession is a type of gingival disease in which the gum tissue around the teeth recedes or pulls back, creating pockets between the tooth and the gum line. This can lead to various problems such as sensitivity, inflammation, and even tooth loss if left untreated. There are different degrees of gingival recession, ranging from mild to severe. Mild recession refers to a small pocket formation between the tooth and gum line, while moderate recession indicates a deeper pocket formation that reaches the cemento-enamel junction. Severe recession involves a pocket depth of 4 millimeters or more below the cemento-enamel junction.

Arcus senilis is a medical condition that affects the cornea, which is the clear, dome-shaped surface at the front of the eye. It is also known as corneal arcus or Arcus of cornea. This condition is characterized by a ring-like deposition of calcium around the periphery of the cornea.

Arcus senilis typically affects people over the age of 60 and is more common in women than men. It is not uncommon for people with arcus senilis to have cataracts or other age-related changes in their vision. However, it is important to note that arcus senilis does not usually cause significant vision problems on its own.

If you have concerns about arcus senilis or any other eye condition, it is always a good idea to consult with an ophthalmologist, who can provide a proper diagnosis and recommend appropriate treatment.
That's correct! Scleral disease refers to a condition that affects the sclera, which is the white fibrous outer layer of the eyeball.

Bladder diverticulum is a condition where pouches or sacs form in the wall of the bladder. It's also sometimes referred to as Diverticulum - bladder, or simply Diverticulum of the bladder. These pouches can become inflamed and cause pain, discomfort, and other symptoms if they become infected or obstruct the normal flow of urine. Bladder diverticulum is typically treated with medications to reduce inflammation and increase fluid intake to help flush out bacteria from the bladder. In some cases, surgery may be necessary to remove the affected tissue.

A bladder diverticulum is a small pouch or pocket that forms in the wall of the bladder. It is common for people to have this condition, but it can also lead to complications if stones form in the diverticulum. A stone in a bladder diverticulum is called a diverticula calculi. It is important to seek medical attention if you experience symptoms such as pain, blood in your urine or difficulty urinating. Your doctor can help diagnose and treat this condition with medication, lifestyle changes, or surgery depending on the severity of the issue.

Bladder calculi, also known as kidney stones or urinary tract stones, occur when minerals and salts in the urine crystallize and form solid masses. These masses can cause blockages in the urinary system, leading to a variety of symptoms such as severe pain, blood in the urine, nausea, vomiting, and difficulty urinating. Bladder calculi are typically diagnosed through imaging tests like X-rays or CT scans, and treated with medications that help dissolve the stones or surgery to remove them. Prevention measures include staying hydrated, maintaining a healthy diet, and avoiding certain medications that can increase the risk of kidney stones forming.

Phlebotomus fever is a type of viral infectious disease that results from infection with the Sandfly fever Naples virus or the Sandfly fever Sicilian virus, which are transmitted by Phlebotomus papatasi sandflies. The infection causes symptoms such as fever, severe frontal headaches, muscle aches, joint aches, flushing of the face, and tachycardia. It is also known as Sandfly fever or pappataci fever.

Subluxation of lens is a medical condition in which the natural lens within the eye is displaced or shifted from its normal position. This can occur due to a variety of factors, including aging, injury, or certain medications. Symptoms may include blurry vision, double vision, and sensitivity to light. Treatment options depend on the severity of the subluxation and can range from corrective lenses to surgical interventions such as cataract extraction or lens replacement. It is important for individuals with subluxated lenses to consult an eye care professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

Congenital aphakia is a type of physical disorder that occurs when an individual is born without a lens in one or both eyes. This can cause severe visual impairment and may require surgical intervention to correct the issue. It is important for individuals with congenital aphakia to receive proper medical care and support to help them live as independently and safely as possible.

Functional diarrhea is a type of gastrointestinal disorder characterized by persistent loose stools, an urgent need to have a bowel movement, and abdominal pain or discomfort. It is also known as functional bowel syndrome, irritable bowel syndrome with diarrhea (IBS-D), or non-infectious diarrhea. Functional diarrhea may be caused by a combination of factors, including altered gut motility, food intolerance, stress, and changes in the gut microbiota. Treatment options for functional diarrhea typically include lifestyle modifications, medications, and, in some cases, surgery.

Megacolon is a term used to describe a type of colorectal condition characterized by the excessive dilatation (widening) of the colon. It can also refer to a congenital narrowing of the colon, which leads to a ballooning or swelling in the area where the two ends of the intestine meet. In some cases, it can be caused by other health problems such as Crohn's disease, diverticulitis or mesenteric ischemia.

Gnathomiasis is a type of parasitic helminthiasis infectious disease characterized by the infection and migration of the larvae of Gnathostoma spinigerum or Gnathostoma hispidum. It can be caused by consuming undercooked fish or poultry that contain third-stage larvae, or by drinking water containing infective second-stage larvae in Cyclops. Symptoms of gnathomiasis include intermittent, migratory, painful, pruritic swellings (cutaneous larva migrans) and cough, hematuria, and ocular involvement (visceral larva migrans). More severe cases can also result in eosinophilic meningitis with myeloencephalitis. The exact synonyms for gnathomiasis include Gnathostomiasis and Infectious Disease by Gnathostoma.

Spinal meningioma is a type of tumor that grows in the spinal canal, which is the space where the spinal cord is located. It is also known as spinal cord meningioma. Spinal meningiomas are typically benign (non-cancerous) and usually grow slowly. They can cause symptoms like back pain, radiculopathy, or myelopathy if they press on the spinal nerves or the spinal cord itself. Spinal meningioma is a type of meningioma that grows in the spinal canal. It's also known as intradural extramedullary tumor. Expressive language disorder is a type of communication disorder that affects an individual's ability to use language expressively, such as in speech or writing. This can lead to challenges with word-finding, sentence construction, and overall language fluency. Epidural abscess is indeed a type of central nervous system disease, and it occurs when there is an infection between the outer covering of the brain and spinal cord (dura mater) and the bones of the skull or spine. This collection of pus can put pressure on the spinal cord, leading to potential neurological complications if not treated promptly. The symptoms of an epidural abscess usually include severe headache, neck stiffness, fever, and nausea. Diagnosis typically involves a combination of imaging studies (such as MRI) and blood tests to identify the presence of bacteria or other pathogens. Treatment often involves surgical drainage of the abscess, along with antibiotics to eliminate any bacterial infection. In more severe cases, hospitalization may be necessary for close monitoring and management of potential complications.

Subdural empyema is a type of central nervous system disease that occurs when there is the collection or gathering of pus within the subdural space. The exact synonym for this condition is Subdural abscess.

Cerebral arteritis, also known as cerebrovascular disease or cerebral vascular disease (CVA), is a condition that affects the blood vessels in the brain. It occurs when the walls of the blood vessels become inflamed and thickened, which can lead to reduced blood flow and increased pressure within the affected vessels. As a result, this can cause damage to the brain tissue and potentially lead to various symptoms such as headaches, confusion, memory problems, and even stroke. Cerebral arteritis is not just one disease but a collection of conditions that affect the cerebrovascular system, including atherosclerosis, aneurysms, and venous sinus thrombosis. Proper diagnosis and treatment are crucial in managing this condition to prevent further complications or long-term damage to the brain.

Adult respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS) is a type of respiratory failure that occurs due to diffuse injury to the endothelium of the lungs, which can be caused by various factors such as sepsis, chest trauma, massive blood transfusion, aspiration of gastric contents, or pneumonia. It is characterized by pulmonary edema with an abnormally high amount of protein in the edematous fluid and difficulty breathing, leading to hypoxemia (low oxygen levels) and rapid shallow breathing. ARDS can also be referred to as acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema (NPE), shock lung, or adult RDS.

Pulmonary edema is a type of respiratory failure that occurs when excess fluid accumulates in the lungs, leading to difficulty breathing and potential respiratory failure. It can be caused by various factors such as heart failure, trauma, or anaphylaxis, and can have serious consequences if not treated promptly.

Heart disease is a term that refers to any condition or illness that affects the heart or cardiovascular system. It can include conditions such as coronary artery disease, arrhythmia, and heart failure, among others. These diseases are typically caused by a combination of genetic, environmental, and lifestyle factors, and can lead to complications like stroke, heart attack, and even death if left untreated.

It is a primary bacterial infectious disease that can lead to potentially life-threatening complications if left untreated.

Brain compression can be caused by various factors such as head injury, brain tumors, infections, or inflammation. It is important to seek medical attention if you suspect that you may have brain compression, as it can lead to serious complications if left untreated. A healthcare professional will likely perform a physical examination and order imaging tests such as CT scans or MRI to diagnose the condition. Treatment options for brain compression depend on the underlying cause and may include medications, surgery, or a combination of both. It is important to work closely with your healthcare provider to develop an appropriate treatment plan based on your specific needs and health status.

Pseudotumor cerebri, also known as benign intracranial hypertension or idiopathic intracranial hypertension, is a condition characterized by increased pressure within the skull. Although it can affect any part of the brain, it is most commonly found in the optic nerves and brainstem.

There are several possible causes for pseudotumor cerebri, but the exact cause remains unknown in many cases. Some potential factors that may contribute to the development of this condition include:

* Genetics: There may be a genetic predisposition to developing pseudotumor cerebri.
* Hormonal changes: Fluctuations in hormone levels, such as those experienced during pregnancy or menopause, can increase the risk of this condition.
* Obstructive sleep apnea: This condition may lead to an increased risk of pseudotumor cerebri due to disrupted sleep patterns and decreased oxygenation of the brain.
* Use of certain medications: Certain drugs, such as corticosteroids or diuretics, can increase intracranial pressure and may contribute to the development of pseudotumor cerebri.

Symptoms of pseudotumor cerebri may include headache, blurred vision, nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light. In some cases, severe headaches can be a sign of a more serious condition called "status migrainosus," which requires immediate medical attention.

Diagnosis of pseudotumor cerebri typically involves a thorough medical history and physical examination, as well as diagnostic testing such as CT or MRI scans. In some cases, a lumbar puncture (spinal tap) may be performed to measure the pressure within the skull and to examine the cerebrospinal fluid for any abnormalities.

Treatment of pseudotumor cerebri depends on the severity of the condition and may involve lifestyle changes, medications, or surgery. In mild cases, lifestyle changes such as weight loss, increased fluid intake, and avoiding certain trigger foods (such as salt) may be sufficient to manage symptoms. In more severe cases, medications such as acetazolamide or furosemide may be prescribed to help reduce intracranial pressure. Surgical intervention, such as a ventriculostomy or an optic nerve sheath decompression procedure, may be necessary in some cases if other treatments are unsuccessful or if the condition is causing significant symptoms or damage.

Osteoporosis is a condition that affects the bones, specifically causing them to become thinner and weaker. It results from an imbalance in calcium levels within the body, leading to a decreased density of mineralized bone. This can make the bones more susceptible to fractures and breaks. There are several factors that contribute to the development of osteoporosis, including age, gender, dietary habits, exercise, and genetic predisposition. Treatment options for osteoporosis typically include medications such as bisphosphonates or denosumab, calcium and vitamin D supplements, as well as lifestyle modifications like increased physical activity and a healthy diet rich in calcium and vitamin D.
